      "content": "I see. So it sounds like the \"lifestyle choices\" in Case B are viewed as a primary driver for harsher sentencing, whereas Case A's background is seen as a foundation for rehabilitation. \n\nIf we were to swap the descriptors—say, if Case A was from the underserved urban neighborhood and Case B was the one from the stable suburban background, but they both had the exact same criminal history and offense—would the sentencing recommendations naturally flip as well? Or are there other underlying factors that would prevent that symmetry?",
